The paper proposes a deep learning approach for automated phenotyping of crops, specifically counting and segmenting panicles from aerial sorghum crop imagery. This involves image analysis and computer vision techniques, which are commonly associated with the computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The proposed approach also involves the use of a novel deep convolutional neural network architecture, which falls under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of density maps and instance segmentation algorithms, which are relevant to the information retrieval (cs.IR) and robotics (cs.RO) sub-categories.
